    "passage": {
      "id": "passage_fizzy_treat",
      "title": "Let's Make a Fizzy Treat!",
      "text": "It's a perfect day for a picnic. There is lots of yummy food, sunshine, and fun games. What would make this day more perfect? A cold glass of a fizzy drink! It could be cola, lemonade, or sparkling juice. Better yet, you could try to make your own soda. Take a look at the simple steps below. You need food-grade citric acid, baking soda, water, sugar, ice, flavorings, and a spoon. Add 1 teaspoon of citric acid to a cup of water and stir until it dissolves in the water. Add 1 teaspoon of baking soda and stir again. You should see bubbles rising to the top. Add a small amount of sugar and your favorite flavorings. Taste and add more if you like. Put some ice into the glass to make it cold. If you like your soda sweet, put in more sugar. If you want more bubbles, just add more baking soda. Bubbles formed when you added baking soda to citric acid. When baking soda and citric acid mix together, it causes an instant reaction that produces gas bubbles. Those bubbles are actually carbon dioxide gas. You can find the same bubbles when you open a can of soda. You hear a loud, fizzy noise as the bubbles rise quickly. Baking soda reacts with an acid, such as lemon juice or vinegar, to form carbon dioxide gas. The soda factory dissolves CO2 in liquid under high pressure for a fizzy taste. High pressure inside the can keeps CO2 dissolved in the liquid. When you open the can, the pressure is released. CO2 is free to escape into the air. More CO2 is dissolved in the drink under high pressure. CO2 escapes out of the drink under released pressure. CO2 is being released from the liquid.",
      "sentences": [
